entry.title: Flood Warning issued September 29 at 9:28PM EDT by NWS Melbourne FL
entry.summary:
...The Flood Warning continues for the following rivers in Florida...
St Johns River Near Astor affecting Volusia and Lake Counties.
.The river is hovering near Minor Flood Stage and should rise higher into Minor Flood Stage early this week due to increasing northerly winds. Additional rises are possible due to persistent northerly winds and anticipated rainfall over the river basin.
For the St. Johns River...including Astor...Minor flooding is forecast.
Additional information is available at www.weather.gov.
The next statement will be issued Tuesday morning at 1100 AM EDT.
* WHAT...Minor flooding is forecast.
* WHERE...St Johns River near Astor.
* WHEN...Until further notice.
* IMPACTS...At 2.3 feet, Many docks become submerged along the river and in canals in the Astor community. Water enters yards of properties on Bartram Road, Holiday Circle and along Wild Hog Road on the Lake County side. In Volusia County, water encroaches yards of homes on the river side of Alice Drive. No wake zones are in effect from near the South Moon Canal to approximately 800 feet south of the Riverview lodge.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS... - At 8:30 PM EDT Monday the stage was 2.3 feet. - Bankfull stage is 2.0 feet. - Forecast...The river is expected to rise above flood stage just after midnight tonight and continue rising to 2.5 feet early Wednesday afternoon. Additional rises are possible thereafter. - Flood stage is 2.3 feet. - http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

entry.title: Severe Thunderstorm Warning issued September 29 at 6:27PM PDT until September 29 at 7:15PM PDT by NWS Boise ID
entry.summary:
SVRBOI
The National Weather Service in Boise has issued a
* Severe Thunderstorm Warning for... Central Malheur County in southeastern Oregon...
* Until 715 PM PDT.
* At 627 PM PDT, a severe thunderstorm was located near Crooked Creek State Park, or 9 miles west of Rome, moving northeast at 35 mph.
HAZARD...60 mph wind gusts and nickel size hail.
SOURCE...Radar indicated.
IMPACT...Expect damage to roofs, siding, and trees.
* Locations impacted include... Iron Point, Sacramento Butte, Crooked Creek State Park, Coffeepot Crater, Owyhee Butte, and Saddle Butte Lava Tube.
Monitoring message only. Please disregard.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued September 29 at 6:13PM PDT by NWS Boise ID
entry.summary:
At 612 PM PDT, Doppler radar was tracking a gust front along a line extending from near Saddle Butte Lava Tube to near Jackies Butte. Movement was north at 65 mph.
HAZARD...Wind gusts up to 50 mph.
SOURCE...Radar indicated.
IMPACT...Gusty winds could knock down tree limbs and blow around unsecured objects. Areas of blowing dust reducing visibility down to half a mile.
Locations impacted include... Rome, Burns Junction, Scott Reservoir, Flat Top Mountain, Crooked Creek State Park, Bowden Hills, Owyhee Butte, Basque Station, Arock, Jackies Butte, Three Man Butte, Saddle Butte Lava Tube, Rome Airport, Round Mountain, and Overshoe Pass.

entry.title: Coastal Flood Warning issued September 29 at 9:06PM EDT until October 3 at 8:00PM EDT by NWS Newport/Morehead City NC
entry.summary:
* WHAT...For the Beach Hazards Statement, dangerous rip currents. For the High Surf Advisory, large breaking waves of 6 to 12 feet in the surf zone. For the Coastal Flood Warning, moderate oceanside coastal flooding expected, with 2 to 3 feet of inundation above ground level expected in low-lying areas near shorelines and tidal waterways. For Downeast Carteret County, minor soundside flooding expected with inundation 1 to 2 feet above ground.
* WHERE...East Carteret County, and Ocracoke Island and Hatteras Island.
* WHEN...For the Beach Hazards Statement, through Tuesday evening. For the High Surf Advisory, until 8 AM EDT Saturday. For the Coastal Flood Warning, from 11 AM Tuesday to 8 PM EDT Friday.
* IMPACTS...Moderate oceanside coastal flooding, with inundation 2 to 3 feet above ground level, locally higher with wave action, resulting in an elevated threat of property damage. Flooding will likely extend inland from the waterfront threatening some homes, businesses and critical infrastructure. Dangerous swimming, surfing conditions and beach erosion expected. Rip currents can sweep even the best swimmers away from shore into deeper water.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Greatest potential for impacts along vulnerable portions of Highway 12 on Ocracoke and Hatteras Islands. Portions of Highway 12 may be impassable at times due to ocean overwash, especially around times of high tide. Minor soundside flooding in Downeast Carteret County also expected.
entry.cap:areaDesc: East Carteret; Ocracoke Island; Hatteras Island

* WHERE...A portion of northeast Nevada, including the following county, Elko.

* IMPACTS...Minor flooding and debris flow activity.
